      <h1>Palfinder Galaxy Service</h1>

      <h2>About this service</h2>
      <p>Pal finder Galaxy is a service is provided by the Bioinformatics
	Core Facility and Research Computing teams at the University of
	Manchester in conjunction with the lab of Richard Preziosi at the
	University of Manchester
	(<a href="http://preziosilab.org">preziosilab.org</a>). This is a
	customised pre-configured Galaxy instance for implementing the
	method of microsatellite development described in Griffiths et al.
	(2016) (for full reference see below).</p>

      <h2>What you can do with this service</h2>
      <p>Users may:</p>
      <ul>
	<li>Create a user account</li>
	<li>Upload Illumina sequence data files</li>
	<li>Use example data files</li>
	<li>Run a microsatellite development pipeline using the following
	  programs within the Galaxy environment:
	  <ul>
	    <li>Fast QC</li>
	    <li>Trimmomatic</li>
	    <li>Pal_finder</li>
	    <li>Pal_filter</li>
	    <li>PANDA_seq</li>
	    <li>Primer3</li>
	  </ul>
	</li>
	<li>Download results files</li>
	<li>Store data for a maximum of {{ delete_datasets_after }}</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Limitations</h2>
      <p>Accounts have a quota of <b>{{ default_quota_gb }} GB</b>. User
	accounts and any data uploaded or generated are automatically
	deleted after <b>{{ delete_datasets_after }}</b>. This is to
	prevent the build up of	large volumes of data onto our servers
	long-term. All outputs generated can be downloaded.</p>
      <p><b>By registering and using this service you agree to be bound by
	  the <a href="terms.html">terms and conditions</a></b>.</p>
      <p>You are advised to consult the user manual for detailed
	instructions and information.</p>

